{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The conversation history passed to the LLM is trimmed to the most recent 10 messages when the full history exceeds the context window.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: the failure boundary is the handoff between history-trimming logic and the LLM request builder (a pure unit test of trimming can miss wrong payload wiring/order). REAL-INFRA/MOCK-HIDE: no real OS/network/subprocess is required; an in-process LLM client stub that captures the outgoing payload is sufficient. LLM-DEP/MULTI-STEP: correctness does not depend on model judgment, only on what is sent. REJECTION-GATE: System/Agentic/Workflow were rejected because behavior text is about message selection/packing before the model call, not real infrastructure or model output quality.","test_description":"Run chatbot request assembly with real history manager + prompt builder modules and a stub LLM transport that records payload. Provide >10 prior messages; assert exactly the most recent 10 (correct order/roles) are sent to the LLM.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.42,"Integration":0.52,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The generated response addresses the customer's question rather than producing a generic or off-topic reply.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: this is output-quality correctness (relevance/off-topic), which depends on real model behavior and can vary run-to-run. A stubbed response would trivially pass and hide real failures. MULTI-STEP: single generation quality check, so Workflow is not strictly required. REJECTION-GATE: Integration was rejected because behavior text explicitly evaluates semantic quality of generated content, not routing/retry infrastructure.","test_description":"Execute prompts against the real model on a curated support-query set with relevance labels/rubric; score whether answers address the question vs generic/off-topic, with repeat runs to account for nondeterminism.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.06,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.82,"Workflow":0.08}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The tone re-check correctly identifies when a response is too formal for a casual-tier customer and triggers regeneration.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: 'correctly identifies' tone appropriateness is model judgment quality; deterministic fakes hide misclassification. The trigger path is orchestration coupled to that judgment. MULTI-STEP: this behavior centers on one judgment-driven handoff (flag -> regenerate), not a full multi-agent pipeline requirement. REJECTION-GATE: Integration was rejected because behavior text requires correctness of tone classification itself, not only that a boolean flag is propagated.","test_description":"Use real tone-check path with casual-tier fixtures containing overly formal drafts; verify formality is flagged and regeneration is invoked, and measure consistency over repeated runs.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.66,"Workflow":0.1}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The full exchange (user message, generated response, any regenerations) is persisted to the database with correct timestamps.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: failure appears at module boundaries (chat orchestration -> persistence layer -> DB schema/transaction handling). REAL-INFRA: no OS/network/subprocess requirement beyond local in-process DB integration; this can be caught with a real local test DB. LLM-DEP: assertions are about persistence integrity/timestamps, not model output quality. REJECTION-GATE: Agentic/Workflow rejected because behavior text checks storage correctness, not semantic quality of model decisions.","test_description":"Run end-to-end application modules with a real local test DB (same ORM/repository code), including a forced regeneration path; assert all exchange records are stored, linked correctly, and timestamps are present and ordered correctly.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.78,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the tone check triggers regeneration, the second response replaces the first — the customer never sees the rejected draft.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: this is a cross-module state-handoff/orchestration invariant (generation -> tone gate -> user-visible output). It is not a single-function unit concern. REAL-INFRA: can be tested in-process without real OS/network. LLM-DEP: behavior text focuses on visibility/replacement semantics once regeneration is triggered, not on whether model judgments are good; trigger can be deterministically injected. INTEGRATION-BRAKE(d): although LLM-involved stages are sequenced, concrete text 'customer never sees the rejected draft' disqualifies needing real model-quality evaluation. REJECTION-GATE: Workflow rejected because the failure target is output gating/state replacement, not correctness of multiple model decisions.","test_description":"Wire orchestrator, tone-gate, and response-delivery modules together; force tone-check trigger and two generated drafts via deterministic stubs; assert only regenerated draft is emitted to customer channel and rejected draft is never exposed.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.58,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.26,"Workflow":0.12}}]}
